A.1 Preliminaries and Assumptions

Let \mathcal{S} = \mathcal{Z} \times \mathcal{M} \subset \mathbb{R}^{d_s} be a closed, bounded (hence complete) Hilbert space with inner product \langle \cdot, \cdot \rangle and induced norm \|\cdot\|. For a given input x \in \mathbb{R}^{d_x}, define the operator G_\theta : \mathcal{S} \to \mathcal{S} as in (2.1) and F_\theta(s) = s - G_\theta(s,x).

Assumption A.1 (Strong Monotonicity).
There exists \mu > 0 such that for all s_1, s_2 \in \mathcal{S},

\langle F_\theta(s_1) - F_\theta(s_2),\; s_1 - s_2 \rangle \ge \mu \|s_1 - s_2\|^2.

Assumption A.2 (Lipschitz Continuity).
There exists L > 0 such that for all s_1, s_2 \in \mathcal{S},

\|F_\theta(s_1) - F_\theta(s_2)\| \le L \|s_1 - s_2\|.

These two assumptions together imply that F_\theta is a strongly monotone and Lipschitz operator. Equivalent to G_\theta being a contraction in the metric induced by the resolvent, but we work directly with F_\theta.

Assumption A.3 (Boundedness of the fixed point).
The unique solution s^* of F_\theta(s)=0 lies in the interior of \mathcal{S}. This is guaranteed by the contractive properties of the high‑level module (see below).

---

A.2 Existence, Uniqueness, and Linear Convergence (Theorem 1)

Theorem 1 (Existence & Uniqueness).
Under Assumptions A.1 and A.2, the equation F_\theta(s) = 0 has a unique solution s^* \in \mathcal{S}. Moreover, the Picard iteration s_{t+1} = G_\theta(s_t, x) converges linearly to s^* with rate \kappa = \sqrt{1 - 2\mu / L^2}.

Proof.

Existence and uniqueness.
Strong monotonicity implies that F_\theta is injective: if F_\theta(s_1)=F_\theta(s_2), then the monotonicity inequality gives \mu \|s_1-s_2\|^2 \le 0, hence s_1=s_2. For a strongly monotone and Lipschitz operator on a Hilbert space, the range is closed and the operator is surjective (this follows from the Minty–Browder theorem; see e.g. Rockafellar, 1976). Therefore there exists s^* with F_\theta(s^*) = 0. Uniqueness follows from injectivity.

Linear convergence.
We rewrite the Picard iteration as a fixed‑point iteration for F_\theta:

s_{t+1} = s_t - F_\theta(s_t).

Let e_t = s_t - s^*. Then

e_{t+1} = e_t - \big(F_\theta(s_t) - F_\theta(s^*)\big) = e_t - \Delta_t,

where \Delta_t = F_\theta(s_t) - F_\theta(s^*). Taking norms and using the strong monotonicity and Lipschitz properties:

\|e_{t+1}\|^2 = \|e_t\|^2 - 2\langle e_t, \Delta_t\rangle + \|\Delta_t\|^2 \le \|e_t\|^2 - 2\mu \|e_t\|^2 + L^2 \|e_t\|^2 = \big(1 - 2\mu + L^2\big) \|e_t\|^2.

The inequality \langle e_t, \Delta_t\rangle \ge \mu \|e_t\|^2 and \|\Delta_t\| \le L \|e_t\| are used. Hence

\|e_{t+1}\| \le \sqrt{1 - 2\mu + L^2}\, \|e_t\|.

Define \kappa = \sqrt{1 - 2\mu + L^2}. Since \mu > 0 and L \ge \mu (otherwise monotonicity would force Lipschitz constant at least \mu), we have 0 \le \kappa < 1. The geometric convergence follows by induction:

\|e_t\| \le \kappa^t \|e_0\|.

∎

