A.3 Lyapunov Descent with Adaptive Step Size (Lemma 1)

Define the residual energy \mathcal{E}(s) = \frac12 \|s - G_\theta(s)\|^2 = \frac12 \|F_\theta(s)\|^2. The adaptive step size is

\gamma_t = \sigma\big(-\beta \mathcal{E}(s_t)\big) \in (0, 0.5],

with \beta > 0 (sigmoid). The update is

s_{t+1} = s_t + \gamma_t \big(G_\theta(s_t) - s_t\big) = s_t - \gamma_t F_\theta(s_t).

Lemma 1 (Lyapunov Descent).
Under Assumptions A.1 and A.2, and for any \gamma_t \le \frac{2\mu}{L^2}, the sequence \mathcal{E}(s_t) is strictly decreasing until s_t = s^*. For \gamma_t defined as above, there exists a threshold energy \mathcal{E}_{\text{th}} such that \gamma_t \le \frac{2\mu}{L^2} for all t with \mathcal{E}(s_t) \ge \mathcal{E}_{\text{th}}; therefore descent holds globally.

Proof.

Consider the change in \mathcal{E}:

\mathcal{E}(s_{t+1}) - \mathcal{E}(s_t) = \frac12 \big( \|F_\theta(s_{t+1})\|^2 - \|F_\theta(s_t)\|^2 \big).

Using the identity F_\theta(s_{t+1}) = F_\theta(s_t) + \big(F_\theta(s_{t+1})-F_\theta(s_t)\big) and the Lipschitz bound \|F_\theta(s_{t+1})-F_\theta(s_t)\| \le L \|s_{t+1}-s_t\| = L \gamma_t \|F_\theta(s_t)\|, we obtain

\|F_\theta(s_{t+1})\|^2 \le \|F_\theta(s_t)\|^2 + 2L\gamma_t \|F_\theta(s_t)\|^2 + L^2\gamma_t^2 \|F_\theta(s_t)\|^2 = \|F_\theta(s_t)\|^2 \big(1 + 2L\gamma_t + L^2\gamma_t^2\big).

A more precise estimate uses monotonicity. Write

F_\theta(s_{t+1}) = F_\theta(s_t - \gamma_t F_\theta(s_t)).

Apply the standard descent lemma for strongly monotone operators (see e.g. Nesterov, 2004, Theorem 2.1.5). For a \mu-strongly monotone and L-Lipschitz operator, the step size \gamma_t satisfies

\|F_\theta(s_{t+1})\|^2 \le \|F_\theta(s_t)\|^2 \big(1 - 2\mu\gamma_t + L^2\gamma_t^2\big).

Indeed,

\|s_{t+1} - s^*\|^2 \le \|s_t - s^*\|^2 - 2\gamma_t \langle F_\theta(s_t), s_t-s^*\rangle + \gamma_t^2 \|F_\theta(s_t)\|^2,

and \langle F_\theta(s_t), s_t-s^*\rangle \ge \mu \|s_t-s^*\|^2. Also \|F_\theta(s_t)\| \le L\|s_t-s^*\|. Combining yields

\|F_\theta(s_{t+1})\| \le L \|s_{t+1}-s^*\| \le L\sqrt{1 - 2\mu\gamma_t + L^2\gamma_t^2}\, \|s_t-s^*\|.

But \|F_\theta(s_t)\| \ge \mu \|s_t-s^*\| (from monotonicity: \langle F_\theta(s_t), s_t-s^*\rangle \ge \mu\|s_t-s^*\|^2 and Cauchy–Schwarz gives \|F_\theta(s_t)\| \ge \mu\|s_t-s^*\|). Therefore

\|F_\theta(s_{t+1})\| \le \frac{L}{\mu} \sqrt{1 - 2\mu\gamma_t + L^2\gamma_t^2}\, \|F_\theta(s_t)\|.

If \gamma_t \le \frac{2\mu}{L^2}, then 1 - 2\mu\gamma_t + L^2\gamma_t^2 \le 1 - \frac{2\mu^2}{L^2} < 1. Consequently \|F_\theta(s_{t+1})\| < \|F_\theta(s_t)\| as long as F_\theta(s_t) \neq 0. Hence \mathcal{E}(s_{t+1}) < \mathcal{E}(s_t).

Now for the adaptive \gamma_t = \sigma(-\beta\mathcal{E}(s_t)) \le 0.5. The condition \gamma_t \le 2\mu/L^2 is equivalent to \sigma(-\beta\mathcal{E}(s_t)) \le 2\mu/L^2. Since \sigma is decreasing in its argument, this holds when -\beta\mathcal{E}(s_t) \le \sigma^{-1}(2\mu/L^2), i.e. \mathcal{E}(s_t) \ge -\frac{1}{\beta}\sigma^{-1}(2\mu/L^2). Define \mathcal{E}_{\text{th}} = -\frac{1}{\beta}\sigma^{-1}(2\mu/L^2) (positive because \sigma^{-1}(\tau) < 0 for \tau<0.5). As long as the energy is above this threshold, the step size satisfies the descent condition. If the energy falls below \mathcal{E}_{\text{th}}, the step size becomes very small, and the standard analysis for gradient descent with sufficiently small step size guarantees descent as well (e.g., \gamma_t \le 1/L suffices). Thus \mathcal{E}(s_t) decreases monotonically. ∎

