A.4 Expected Error Reduction for Warm‑Started Trajectories (Proposition 1)

We consider K parallel trajectories, each initialised as s_0^{(i)} = s_0^{\text{base}} + \varepsilon_i with \varepsilon_i \sim \mathcal{N}(0,\sigma^2 I). After T steps, the residual energies \mathcal{E}_T^{(i)} = \mathcal{E}(s_T^{(i)}) are random variables. Assume they are i.i.d. with cumulative distribution function F_{\mathcal{E}}(t) = \Pr(\mathcal{E}_T^{(i)} \le t).

Proposition 1 (Expected Error Reduction).

\mathbb{E}\left[ \min_{i=1,\dots,K} \mathcal{E}_T^{(i)} \right] \le \int_0^\infty \big(1 - F_{\mathcal{E}}(t)\big)^K \, dt.

Moreover, if F_{\mathcal{E}} is light‑tailed (e.g., sub‑Gaussian), the right‑hand side decays as \mathcal{O}(1/K).

Proof.

Let E_{\min} = \min_i \mathcal{E}_T^{(i)}. For any non‑negative random variable X, \mathbb{E}[X] = \int_0^\infty \Pr(X > t)\, dt. Hence

\mathbb{E}[E_{\min}] = \int_0^\infty \Pr(E_{\min} > t)\, dt = \int_0^\infty \prod_{i=1}^K \Pr(\mathcal{E}_T^{(i)} > t)\, dt = \int_0^\infty \big(1 - F_{\mathcal{E}}(t)\big)^K \, dt,

where independence is used. This proves the bound.

For the asymptotic rate, note that for light‑tailed distributions, 1 - F_{\mathcal{E}}(t) \le C e^{-c t} for large t. Then

\int_0^\infty (1-F_{\mathcal{E}}(t))^K dt \le \int_0^\infty C^K e^{-c K t} dt = \frac{C^K}{cK}.

Hence \mathbb{E}[E_{\min}] = \mathcal{O}(1/K). ∎

The warm‑start s_0^{\text{base}} ensures that the initial distribution is concentrated in a low‑energy region, making F_{\mathcal{E}} light‑tailed and improving the constant.

