A.5 Implicit Differentiation and Neumann Series (Theorem 2)

We differentiate the fixed‑point equation s^* = G_\theta(s^*, x). For a scalar loss \mathcal{L}(s^*), the gradient w.r.t. \theta is

\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial \theta} = \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial s^*}^\top \frac{\partial s^*}{\partial \theta},

with

\frac{\partial s^*}{\partial \theta} = \big(I - DG_\theta(s^*)\big)^{-1} \frac{\partial G_\theta}{\partial \theta}\big|_{s^*}.

Theorem 2 (Convergence of Neumann Series).
If \rho(DG_\theta(s^*)) \le \kappa < 1, then (I - DG_\theta(s^*)) is invertible and

(I - DG_\theta(s^*))^{-1} = \sum_{i=0}^\infty DG_\theta(s^*)^i,

with geometric convergence in operator norm: \| \sum_{i=0}^{M-1} DG_\theta^i - (I - DG_\theta)^{-1} \| \le \frac{\kappa^M}{1-\kappa}.

Proof.

The spectral radius condition \rho(DG) < 1 implies that the Neumann series converges in operator norm (see e.g. Kress, 2014, Theorem 1.4). Since I - DG is invertible and its inverse is given by the series, the error after M terms is bounded by

\left\| \sum_{i=M}^\infty DG^i \right\| \le \sum_{i=M}^\infty \|DG\|^i \le \sum_{i=M}^\infty \kappa^i = \frac{\kappa^M}{1-\kappa},

where we use \|DG\| \le \rho(DG) + \epsilon = \kappa after choosing an appropriate norm (e.g., the spectral norm). ∎

In practice we compute the vector‑Jacobian product (I - DG)^{-\top} v by solving (I - DG)^\top u = v via the same Neumann series applied to DG^\top (since \rho(DG^\top)=\rho(DG)). The exact implementation uses torch.autograd.functional.vjp to compute DG^\top v without materialising the full matrix.

