A.6 Stability of the Lifted Hierarchical Structure

We show that the lifted design (contractive high‑level, near‑unitary low‑level) can satisfy the strong monotonicity condition if the cross‑coupling terms are sufficiently small.

Let J_H = \frac{\partial f_H}{\partial z^H}, J_{HL} = \frac{\partial f_H}{\partial z^L}, J_{LH} = \frac{\partial f_L}{\partial z^H}, J_L = \frac{\partial f_L}{\partial z^L}, and similarly for the memory Jacobians. The joint Jacobian of G_\theta is block‑structured:

DG = \begin{bmatrix}
J_H & J_{HL} & \frac{\partial f_H}{\partial m} \\[4pt]
J_{LH} & J_L & \frac{\partial f_L}{\partial m} \\[4pt]
\frac{\partial \mathcal{M}}{\partial z} & \frac{\partial \mathcal{M}}{\partial z} & \frac{\partial \mathcal{M}}{\partial m}
\end{bmatrix}.

The monotonicity of F = I - G is equivalent to \frac{1}{2}(DG + DG^\top) \preceq (1-\mu)I for some \mu>0 (if F is differentiable). A sufficient condition is that the symmetric part of DG has eigenvalues bounded above by 1-\mu. If we enforce \|J_H\| \le k_H < 1 and \|J_L\| \le k_L with k_L close to 1, and make the cross‑terms and memory Jacobians sufficiently small (e.g., by scaling the outputs or using spectral normalisation on the coupling layers), then the maximum eigenvalue of \frac{1}{2}(DG+DG^\top) can be kept below 1-\mu. This satisfies Assumption A.1. In practice we do not need an explicit bound; we regularise the minimal eigenvalue of J_F (as in the training objective) to enforce strong monotonicity.

