A.7 Additional Technical Lemmas

Lemma A.1 (Boundedness of Warm‑Start).
If \Pi_\theta is Lipschitz with constant C_\Pi and \|x\| \le B_x, then \|s_0^{\text{base}}\| \le C_\Pi B_x. The perturbations \varepsilon_i are bounded with high probability, so the initial states lie in a bounded region \mathcal{S}_0 \subset \mathcal{S}. The iteration remains in \mathcal{S} if G_\theta maps \mathcal{S} into itself (ensured by contractive activations and bounded memory).

Proof.
Trivial from Lipschitz continuity and the fact that Gaussian perturbations are sub‑Gaussian; a standard tail bound gives \|\varepsilon_i\| \le \sigma\sqrt{d_s + 2\log(1/\delta)} with probability 1-\delta. ∎

Lemma A.2 (Monotonicity Regulariser).
The loss term \mathcal{L}_{\text{mono}} = \lambda_{\text{mono}} \max(0, \mu - \lambda_{\min}(J_F)) encourages the minimal eigenvalue of the symmetric part of J_F to be at least \mu, which is equivalent to strong monotonicity with constant \mu for a differentiable operator.

Proof.
For a differentiable F, strong monotonicity with constant \mu is equivalent to \nabla F(s) + \nabla F(s)^\top \succeq 2\mu I for all s (see Nesterov, 2004, Theorem 2.1.2). The regulariser penalises violations of this condition. ∎

